<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-683-847  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 683 847.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Dec 3 1990 n298 p50(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Man-to-man networking: metropolitan area networks gain popularity.andO;(includes related article on activities of companies that bypasslocal telephone exchanges)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Miles, J.B.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber-optic metropolitan area networks (MANs) have grown from afew systems generating less than $20 million in revenues for threealternative local carriers in 1987 to a projected 40 MANsproducing $224 million in revenues nationwide by the end of 1991.andO;MANs can provide thousands of local computer systems withsufficient bandwidth to transfer data, images, voice and video atT1 (1.544M-bps), T3 (45M-bps) and even higher speeds.andP;  Originalmarket emphases on high bandwidth, flexibility and lower cost havebeen superseded by concern for quality, installation speed,redundancy and customer service.andP;  The desire for all-digital,wide-bandwidth communications systems and the growth of local areanetworks in corporations are among the factors driving thealternative carrier fiber-optic MAN market.andP;  Telephone companiesare responding with a variety of technologies to compete with theMAN services.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Metropolitan Area NetworksTrendsCompetitionFiber OpticsOptical CommunicationsMarket AnalysisUser NeedsDigital Communications.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphphotograph.andO;Caption:   What users want from MANs: 1985-1990. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>